 straight when something like this was dumped into their lap.
 In fact, Haslush wasn't the first person they were contacting about this, and
 he wouldn't be the last, but he was the one who had had the best reaction thus
 far.
 This didn't mean he would end up being useful in the end, of course, but it
 was encouraging.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I don't know," the simulacrum said.
 "Although it may seem like I'm holding all the cards here, I'm actually not
 sure what should be done here.
 I'm not a professional spy or master manipulator.
 I'm hoping that you will know what to do with this better than I do."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Haslush stared at him quietly for a second before leafing through the pages a
 few more times.
 It was just an idle gesture.
 The simulacrum could see he wasn't really reading things, just idly flipping
 through the documents and he mulled things over.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He eventually snapped the paper holder shut and pushed it aside before
 massaging his temples for a bit.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"This is insane," he said.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, you already said that," the simulacrum noted.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Well, I feel like repeating myself," Haslush told him, giving him a weak
 glare.
 "I suppose this does help explain all the weird attacks and sudden deaths my
 department has been flooded with lately.
 Who else did you tell about this?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"What makes you think I told others?" the simulacrum asked, surprised.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Who?" Haslush insisted, not offering any explanations.

